        "body": "Psalm 8 opens not with petition but with exclamation. *O LORD, our Lord* — Hebrew *YHWH adoneinu* — fuses the covenant name revealed at Sinai with the title of sovereign mastery. The God who is *our* God by covenant is *Lord* by absolute right; the relationship is not democratic. The exclamation that follows takes the form of a rhetorical *mah* (how, what) — the same word that will return at verse 4 as the question *what is man*. The psalm's rhetorical structure is bound together by this single word doing double duty: *how majestic* (1, 9) brackets *what is man* (4), and the smallness of the creature inside the brackets only magnifies the majesty proclaimed by them.\n\nThe scope is total. *In all the earth* — God's *shem* (name, reputation, self-disclosed character) fills the horizontal sphere of the entire created world. And *above the heavens* — His *hod* (splendor, weight of glory) exceeds even the vertical sphere of the cosmos. There is no realm where His majesty is not the controlling reality. Israel's God is not a regional deity bound to a tribe or a territory; He is the cosmic Sovereign whose reputation fills heaven and earth. Calvin reads this as the foundational confession of all true worship — until God is recognized as Lord of *all* the earth and *above* the heavens, every other religious claim is a diminishment.\n\nVerse 2 introduces the psalm's first paradox: *From the mouth of infants and nursing babes You have established strength because of Your adversaries, to make the enemy and the revengeful cease.* The Hebrew is striking — *olelim* (toddlers, small children) and *yonqim* (nursing babes, still at the breast) are the weakest, least articulate voices in the human community. Through them, God *establishes strength* (*yasad oz*) — founds, anchors, sets in place a bulwark — that silences His adversaries. The argument is not merely sentimental; it is the consistent biblical pattern that God uses the weak to shame the strong (1 Samuel 17; 1 Corinthians 1:27-29). The verse becomes the punchline of Matthew 21:16, where Jesus quotes it against the chief priests who object to children crying *Hosanna* in the temple: the praise that humbles the proud comes from the mouths the proud most despise.\n\nThe pastoral force is twofold. First, God's vindication of His name does not depend on the eloquent or the powerful; in the economy of grace, the weakest voices carry the strongest testimony. Second, the *enemies* of verse 2 — *the enemy and the revengeful* — are not external pagans in this psalm's argument; they are the proud who refuse to acknowledge YHWH's majesty. Their refusal is overturned not by force but by praise. The whole psalm, in fact, is itself a piece of that ordained strength — a song from a single human mouth that, sung corporately, silences every counter-claim to God's glory.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *YHWH adoneinu* — the personal covenant name fused with the lordship-title; *addir* (majestic) is the same word used of crashing seas (Psalm 93:4) and of God Himself as supreme over rivals. *Yasad oz* (established strength) — to lay a foundation, to anchor; the LXX reads *katartizō ainon* (*prepared praise*) in 8:2, which is the form Jesus quotes in Matthew 21:16. The Hebrew and Greek are complementary: praise *is* the strength by which God's adversaries are unseated."
