      {
        "number": 5,
        "title": "The closing inclusio — wonder confirmed (8:9)",
        "range": "8:9",
        "excerpt": "O LORD, our Lord, how majestic is Your name in all the earth!",
        "body": "The psalm ends exactly where it began. Verse 9 repeats verse 1 word-for-word in Hebrew: *YHWH adoneinu, mah-addir shimkha be-khol-ha-arets!* But the repetition is not redundancy — it is *informed* wonder. The opening exclamation was the confession of a worshiper looking up; the closing exclamation is the confession of a worshiper who has now traced God's majesty through the heavens (1), through the silencing of the proud by infant voices (2), through the fingerwork of moon and stars (3), through the astonishing dignity granted to mortal man (4-5), and through the dominion catalog of land, air, and sea (6-8). The same six words now carry the weight of the whole meditation.\n\nThe Hebrew poetic device is *inclusio* — bookend repetition that frames a unit and signals that everything between bookends serves the bookended claim. Psalm 8's whole argument is *YHWH's name is majestic in all the earth.* The body proves it. The closing reasserts it. The reader is invited to read the psalm again — and again, and again — letting each reading deepen what the bookends declare.\n\nWhat the inclusio also does is *resist* the temptation to make Psalm 8 anthropocentric. The middle of the psalm celebrates man — his dignity, his crown, his dominion. A modern reader, untrained in inclusio, might walk away thinking the psalm is *about* humanity. The bookends prevent that. The psalm is about God's *name* — His revealed character, His self-disclosed majesty. Man's dignity is not the center; man's dignity is one of the proofs of God's majesty. The God who could create such a creature, crown such a creature, and entrust such a creature with dominion is a God whose majesty fills all the earth. Anthropology serves theology. The crown on man's head is a testimony to the glory of the One who placed it there.\n\nFor the believer, Psalm 8 ends therefore as it began — but with reasons multiplied. The same exclamation is now spoken with deeper warrant. And when the New Testament reads the psalm Christologically, the warrant deepens again: the *True* Son of Man who holds the dominion of verse 6 is the eternal Son of God incarnate, crucified, risen, and reigning. The God whose name is majestic in all the earth has revealed that majesty climactically not in the moon and stars but in the Man Jesus Christ, crowned with glory and honor because of the suffering of death (Hebrews 2:9). Psalm 8 sung by Christians sings of Christ — and through Christ, of the redeemed humanity He is leading back into the dominion Adam lost.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** The *inclusio* form is one of the most common structural devices in Hebrew poetry — see also Psalm 103:1, 22 (*Bless the LORD, O my soul*) and Psalm 118:1, 29 (*Give thanks to the LORD, for He is good*). The repetition is never lazy; it is the poet's signal of thesis. Psalm 8's bookends declare: *this is what the psalm is about, and this is what you should walk away believing.*"
      }
